<div id="review_1514289856" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1514289856" />
    <a title="Jeanette" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11869072-jeanette"><img alt="Jeanette" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1372095557p2/11869072.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1514289856?book_show_action=true">Jan 17, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeanette" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeanette" href="/user/show/11869072-jeanette">Jeanette</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1514289856" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9816725379015767597">Strange and bizarre characters, each with their own peccadillos stand at three sides of a love triangle. Oh wait, are there at times 4 sides. Or at one time five sides?<br/><br/>Yes, it&apos;s baking and it&apos;s gnarly. And it&apos;s in Faulkner country and also, IMHO, attempts Faulkner like language. Style wise anyway. Holding lengthy, complicated by four verbal phrases at minimum sentences, at that. But not always.<br/><br/>It&apos;s grit. lit. before the ever present foul language of that genre? Also without the drugs. <br/><br/>Regardless</span>
  <span id="freeText9816725379015767597" style="display:none">Strange and bizarre characters, each with their own peccadillos stand at three sides of a love triangle. Oh wait, are there at times 4 sides. Or at one time five sides?<br /><br />Yes, it's baking and it's gnarly. And it's in Faulkner country and also, IMHO, attempts Faulkner like language. Style wise anyway. Holding lengthy, complicated by four verbal phrases at minimum sentences, at that. But not always.<br /><br />It's grit. lit. before the ever present foul language of that genre? Also without the drugs. <br /><br />Regardless, it nails these characters. Amy is the present day nasty girl man user. Harley the social climber and two faced misogynist that we meet in so many current moderns. But their depths of avarice are nearly 5 star in plot, locale, form. 4.5 star and Shelby Foote could write.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9816725379015767597" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

