<div id="review_4068811522" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4068811522" />
    <a title="JerryDeanHalleck" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33221546-jerrydeanhalleck"><img alt="JerryDeanHalleck" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4068811522?book_show_action=true">Jun 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="JerryDeanHalleck" class="user" itemprop="url" name="JerryDeanHalleck" href="/user/show/33221546-jerrydeanhalleck">JerryDeanHalleck</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4068811522" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer179471533053403720">I&apos;m a big fan of Shelby Foote&apos;s civil war books, and <b>Love in a Dry Season </b> is the first Foote novel, that I&apos;ve read. Very enjoyable. Great prose style and the plot is well constructed. Every time I felt the story was going turn cliché, it surprised me. (I especially enjoyed that the story didn&apos;t evolve into a police thriller or <i>Double Indemnity in the Delta</i>). Four of the six main characters are dislikable or dysfunctional, but they&apos;re well-drawn and their motivations are understandable even if n</span>
  <span id="freeText179471533053403720" style="display:none">I'm a big fan of Shelby Foote's civil war books, and <b>Love in a Dry Season </b> is the first Foote novel, that I've read. Very enjoyable. Great prose style and the plot is well constructed. Every time I felt the story was going turn cliché, it surprised me. (I especially enjoyed that the story didn't evolve into a police thriller or <i>Double Indemnity in the Delta</i>). Four of the six main characters are dislikable or dysfunctional, but they're well-drawn and their motivations are understandable even if not admirable. Foote manages to breathe some life into what are now, stock Southern Gothic figures - i.e. The oppressive, rigid father, the "crazy" daughter in the attic, the pathetic spinster, and the promiscuous rich girl. <br /><br />Its a tribute to Foote's talent for character building, that at the end, I felt disappointment over the lack of retributive justice, but I got over it, when I realized every character stayed true to themselves. Their endings were realistic. After all, true justice is often NOT served.<br /><br />In any case, the real star of the novel is not characters, but the town itself. Foote describes it, and the supporting characters with a sure hand. He had first-hand knowledge of the prewar Mississippi Delta and it shows. He makes it an attractive and believable place, despite our dysfunctional main characters. <br /><br />Ordinarily, I would give the book of this quality 5 stars, but I deduct one star for the lack of positive characters and the downbeat story. Like Faulkner, Shelby Foote hits the negative a little too hard. I know its easier to write weirdness/evil then goodness and normality - but one wishes for some of it anyway. <br /><br />Listened to on Audiobook and the narrator did an excellent job.</span>
  <a data-text-id="179471533053403720" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


